CheckedListBox+CheckedItemCollection Class

In this Article

Encapsulates the collection of checked items, including items in an indeterminate state, in a CheckedListBox control.

Syntax

Declaration

public class CheckedListBox.CheckedItemCollection : System.Collections.IList

Inheritance Hierarchy

  • System.Object
  • CheckedListBox+CheckedItemCollection

Inherited Members

,

GetType()
,

,
ReferenceEquals(Object,Object)
,
ToString()

Remarks

The checked items collection is a subset of all items in the CheckedListBox control; it contains only those items that are in a checked or indeterminate state.

The following table is an example of the indexed collection of items in the control (all items contained in the control).

Index Item Check State
0 object 1 CheckState
1 object 2 CheckState
2 object 3 CheckState
3 object 4 CheckState
4 object 5 CheckState

Based on the previous example, the following table shows the indexed collection of the checked items.

Index Item
0 object 2
1 object 4
2 object 5

The CheckedListBox class has two members that allow you to access the stored indexes, the Item property and the IndexOf method.

Based on the previous example, a call to the Item property with a parameter value of 1 returns object 4. A call to IndexOf with a parameter of object 4 returns a value of 1.

Properties

  • Count

    Gets the number of items in the collection.

    public int Count { get; }

    Property Value

    • Int32

      The number of items in the collection.

  • IsReadOnly

    Gets a value indicating if the collection is read-only.

    public bool IsReadOnly { get; }

    Property Value

    • Boolean

      Always true.

  • Item(Int32)

    Gets an object in the checked items collection.

    public object this[int index] { get; set; }

    Parameters

    • index
      Int32

      An index into the collection of checked items. This collection index corresponds to the index of the checked item.

    Property Value

    • System.Object

      The object at the specified index. For more information, see the examples in the CheckedListBox+CheckedItemCollection class overview.

    Exceptions

    • NotSupportedException

      The object cannot be set.

    Remarks

    The CheckedItems collection is a subset of the objects in the Items collection, representing only items that are checked. This collection is ordered in ascending order.

Methods

  • Contains(Object)

    Determines whether the specified item is located in the collection.

    public bool Contains (object item);

    Parameters

    • item
      System.Object

      An object from the items collection.

    Returns

    • Boolean

      true if item is in the collection; otherwise, false.

    Remarks

    This method determines if an object from the Items collection is in the CheckedItems collection.

  • CopyTo(Array,Int32)

    Copies the entire collection into an existing array at a specified location within the array.

    public void CopyTo (Array dest, int index);

    Parameters

    • dest
      Array

      The destination array.

    • index
      Int32

      The zero-based relative index in dest at which copying begins.

    Exceptions

    • ArgumentNullException

      array is null.

    • RankException

      array is multidimensional.

    • ArgumentOutOfRangeException

      index is less than zero.

    • ArgumentException

      The number of elements in the source Array is greater than the available space from index to the end of the destination Array.

    • ArrayTypeMismatchException

      The type of the source Array cannot be cast automatically to the type of the destination Array.

    Remarks

    You can use this method to combine the selected indexes from multiple collections into a single array.

  • GetEnumerator()

    Returns an enumerator that can be used to iterate through the stem.Windows.Forms.CheckedListBox.CheckedItems* collection.

    public System.Collections.IEnumerator GetEnumerator ();

    Returns

    • IEnumerator

      An IEnumerator for navigating through the list.

  • IndexOf(Object)

    Returns an index into the collection of checked items.

    public int IndexOf (object item);

    Parameters

    • item
      System.Object

      The object whose index you want to retrieve. This object must belong to the checked items collection.

    Returns

    • Int32

      The index of the object in the checked item collection or -1 if the object is not in the collection. For more information, see the examples in the CheckedListBox+CheckedItemCollection class overview.

    Remarks

    The CheckedItems collection is a subset of the objects in the Items collection, representing only items that are checked. This collection is ordered in ascending order.
